Commentary.Commentary: So in a pitch where there is spin on offer, it was the pacer who did the damage in the opening hour. That might excite the fast bowlers of New Zealand. Join us in a while for Sri Lanka's reply.

A good day for Sri Lanka, especially Suranga Lakmal. 5 wickets fell and 4 of them fell to Lakmal. The hosts started the day in the best of fashion as Ross Taylor departed without scoring any runs today. The lower order did put up a fight and managed to take the score close to 250, thanks to small but vital contributions from Southee, Boult and unbeaten Somerville.

Pitch Report - Kyle Mills is down doing the pitch report. Mills says that it was consistent on Day 1 and he expects it to be the same. Looking at the surface, Mills says that there are patches and the pitch will crumble as the day progresses, meaning that the footmarks will come into play.

Gritty runs, spinning track, a 5-fer for a spinner and rain. Barring the last, it was a proper subcontinent Test match. New Zealand started off slowly but steadily but the introduction of Akila Dananjaya turned the tide in Sri Lanka's favour. Ross Taylor though is still out there in the middle and he holds the key here for the Kiwis. With good amount of spin on offer, the hosts, will be looking to bundle out New Zealand under 250. Welcome to the coverage of Day 2 of this 1st Test between Sri Lanka and New Zealand as an exciting day of Test cricket awaits us at Galle.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

AN EARLY START IS SCHEDULED AT 9.45 AM LOCAL (0415 GMT) come Thursday. This is of course, weather permitting. The forecast is very grim but hopefully, like it was proved wrong on Wednesday, it is proved incorrect again. New Zealand will look at Ross Taylor to do a Steve Smith and take them to 300. The Lankans on the other hand will look to wrap them up inside 250. Join us to see what happens. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Post Lunch, the Lankans seemed to be giving away the advantage through a 100-run stand between Taylor and Nicholls but like in the first session, Dananjaya struck with 15 minutes to Tea and got the Kiwis 5 down. After that, Rosco tried to counter-attack but rain had the final say.

Right. Whose day was it? Akila Dananjaya's? For sure. Ross Taylor's? Ummm... actually a good shout too! It seemed like a good toss to win when Kane Williamson called correctly and the 64-run stand for the opening wicket set the right tone. But then, with 15 minutes remaining in the first session, Akila Dananjaya struck, reducing the Black Caps to 71/3.

Less than 30 overs left in the day. This could be a make-or-break session for both teams. There is one hero on either side but both heroes need some support. It would be unfair on the Lankans to expect Akila to pick up all the 10 wickets while Rosco alone cannot be scoring runs for the Kiwis. If the Lankans can restrict the Black Caps under 250, they are very well within a shout. On the flip side, if the Kiwis cross 250 and get to 275 and above, boy, they can make the ball talk on this pitch as well. Join us back at 3 pm local (0930 GMT).

Welcome back after the break. Boy, have we waited and waited for Lunch to end! Excited to see the ball spin and make heads turn. Do New Zealand have any fightback plan? Henry Nicholls to join Ross Taylor in the middle.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

Hard to explain New Zealand's state of mind for now. They did all the hard part, seeing off the new ball and would have seen off the session as well but spin did them in. 71/3 looks so different from 64/0. In fact, it looks devastating. The Lankans will now be smiling because this is their territory. Spin it like a cobra and sting the opponents. They will hope to run through the middle order after the break. Join us back at 12.40 pm local (0710 GMT) for the second session.

Akila Dananjaya was bowling against the wind in his first spell and after 2 overs, he changed ends, which immediately bore fruit. He got the ball to land in the right areas and caused doubts in the minds of the batsmen. That indecision caused Latham to think twice before playing or not playing, while Williamson spooned one to the leg side and in the final over before Lunch, Raval edged one behind. Akila, along with the turn but more because of his variations, has eked out all the three wickets.

When Kane Williamson called it correctly this morning at the toss, it seemed like half the battle was won. And when the Black Caps added 64 without losing a wicket, it did look like a long day was in store for the Lankans, with nothing much on offer. But that is the beauty of Test cricket. For minutes and hours, it seems like nothing is happening and when it eventually starts to happen, you cannot believe it has happened. Something similar has occurred here.

Wow. Wow-o-wow-o-w. After 105 minutes of snooze fest, where nothing much was going the bowling team's way, all of a sudden, in the span of 15 minutes, Akila Dananjaya has brought the game to life. Two set batsmen and one synonym to a glue which cannot be separated, have been sent back to the pavilion. Boy, this game is alive and kicking.

It comes in, takes the outside edge and goes low to first slip where Dhananjaya de Silva takes it by coming forward. LUNCH ON DAY 1!

That's 'Namo, Namo, Namo, Namo Matha' done and we are all set to begin. Nice breeze blowing across the ground and should assist the seamers. Tom Latham and Jeet Raval are the openers for the Kiwis, with the latter on strike. Suranga Lakmal will start off proceedings for this day, match, series and tour. Straightaway, a short leg in place, along with two slips. Here we go. Let's play, mates!

Right. The players are out in the middle with some new clothing as the number and name gets printed on their white shirts. Something new, which was started in the Ashes a fortnight ago. Time for the national anthems. New Zealand's first, followed by Sri Lanka's.

Sri Lanka Playing XI - Dimuth Karunaratne(c), Lahiru Thirimanne, Kusal Mendis, Angelo Mathews, Kusal Perera, Niroshan Dickwella(wk), Dhananjaya de Silva, Akila Dananjaya, Lasith Embuldeniya, Suranga Lakmal and Lahiru Kumara.
New Zealand Playing XI - Jeet Raval, Tom Latham, Kane Williamson(c), Ross Taylor, Henry Nicholls, BJ Watling(wk), Mitchell Santner, Tim Southee, William Somerville, Trent Boult and Ajaz Patel.

Sri Lankan captain, Dimuth Karunaratne, says that he too, was looking to bat first as the track usually turns a lot but now, wants to bowl well first and take early wickets. On the new faces in the side, Dimuth says that they did well in South Africa and wants them to do their basics right and compete hard. Informs that Lakmal and Kumara are playing and the spin options are Akila, Dhananjaya and Embuldeniya.

New Zealand skipper, Kane Williamson, says that it looks a good surface to bat, hence the reason. Admits that rain has robbed them of practice but backs his experienced guys to do well on a challenging surface. On Test cricket not being played since February for the Kiwis, Kane says that it is how the international calendar goes. Informs that Colin de Grandhomme misses out for this game.
TOSS - Time for the spin of the coin. Kane Williamson calls Tails and Tails it is. NEW ZEALAND WILL BAT FIRST. That is half the battle won.

PITCH REPORT - Russell Arnold observing the track says that it seems a very good-looking one but very different from the usual Galle one, citing plenty of grass, which could assist seam bowling early on. But from Day 3, spinners should take control.
WEATHER - It was raining the whole of Tuesday and even on match day but at the time of game start, bright sunshine appeared. But the forecast says rain for all the five days.

As far as Sri Lanka are concerned, they have been struggling with the white ball but with the red ball, they have not been that bad. They beat South Africa at home, then the West Indies away and the Proteas away again. The last one was without that champion, Rangana Herath and that victory should certainly boost their spirits. Here they are, at their fortress, Galle.

The Black Caps enter this series on the back of 5 successive Test series wins and if we extend that to 7 in the last 8, it just showcases their dominance. However, only one of those 8 has come outside Kiwiland, hence, this will be a big test of Kane Williamson and his men's character.

Aha... that smell of the morning wet mud on the ground. The sight of the wet grass which has just been watered. The sun shining high in the sky. And... red ball! Woohoo! Test cricket. After days and weeks and months of continuous white-ball cricket, the red-ball stuff comes into focus. Yes, the Ashes have already begun but from this day, we could see a plethora of red-ball games, something which this sport badly needs to avoid imbalance. It is Sri Lanka and New Zealand to kickstart the Test championship in Asia, with the Aussie and the Brits already inagurating it. Who will win? Sri Lanka? New Zealand? Rain? Oops... certainly not the last, we hope. Hello and a warm welcome to the opening day of the first Test between Sri Lanka and New Zealand at Galle.

It is now probably a one innings showdown! If New Zealand bat well and get somewhere close to 250, they will be favourites but it will not be easy to do so. Sri Lanka on the other hand, will not want to chase a lot in the 4th innings for which they will need to keep picking wickets at regular intervals. For now, there is around 50 minutes for Lunch and the hosts will hope to take a couple before that. Another interesting passage awaits ahead. Stay tuned.

At one stage, it never looked like they would go into the lead when they were 161 for 7 after Ajaz Patel, who was easily the pick of the bowlers ran through the Sri Lankan batting line up but then came the fight back from Dickwella and Lakmal. The two added an 81-run stand and took the hosts close to New Zealand's total. Lakmal was dismissed in the 40s but Dickwella continued. He got to a half ton but could not score a lot after that as Somerville got him and the last wicket.

After a decent finish for Sri Lanka yesterday evening, they have managed to have a decent morning today as well. They have managed to add 40 runs which means they have taken a lead. It is a slender one but any kind of lead could be handy.

The replays roll in and the Hawk Eye shows that it was hitting the stumps. SRI LANKA ARE BOWLED OUT FOR 267! THEY LEAD BY 18!

We are all set to begin Day 3. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. Niroshan Dickwella and Suranga Lakmal will resume their innings. Trent Boult will start the proceedings for Day 3. Also, the new ball has been taken.

Pitch report - Kyle Mills is out there for the Pitch report and he says that there is a little bit of grass on the wicket which is unusual in Galle. He further states that there will be help for the faster bowlers as the new ball is due.

A warm welcome to Day 3 of the first Test between New Zealand and Sri Lanka at Galle. The game is evenly poised at the moment with the hosts trailing by another 22 runs with three wickets in hand. The current pair batting out there are amidst a decent stand and Sri Lanka would hope for them to continue and also the batters to come in to contribute and help them take any sort of a lead. On the other hand, New Zealand would look to bundle out the Sri Lankan innings as quickly as possible. The weather forecast ain't that great for today but for now, there is no rain. An important first hour of cricket awaits.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

So we are done with Day 2 of this first Test and we still do not know who is on top of this game.  A very crucial Day 3 awaits us as we might get a clear favorite. Join us on Friday, i.e., 16th August, 2019 at 0945 Local (0415 GMT) for the coverage of Day 3.  The weather forecast looks dodgy but let us hope we have a full day's play as we had on Day 2. Join us for the coverage of Day 3, till then cheers!

As for New Zealand's bowling, Ajaz Patel was the star, picking up 5 out of the 7 to have fallen in this innings. Boult and Somerville were the other two who got into the wickets column. Williamson though will be disappointed that his bowlers could not break the Dickwella-Lakmal stand.

From 143/2 Sri Lanka found themselves at 161/7. It looked like it was all done and they would struggle to get to even 200. But Lakmal and Dickwella had other ideas. They joined hands and decided that they will not go down without a fight. The two have added 66-runs and have reduced the deficit to just 22 now and will now look to overtake the deficit now.

What a fight from Lakmal and Dickwella! An even day of Test cricket. After bundling out New Zealand for 249 earlier in the day courtesy of Lakmal, who scalped 4 wickets today. Sri Lanka started off steadily. They lost two wickets for 66 runs but Kusal Mendis and  Angelo Mathews then steadied the ship and stitched together a 77-run stand, with Mendis registering his 10th Test fifty. He though did not last long after that and departed soon after registering his milestone. Perera too vanished quickly and just like Mendis, Mathews followed suite after getting to his 50.

Tea! A tiring session for New Zealand but the wicket they got in the end will definitely boost their confidence. The start and end belonged to New Zealand but the pair of Angelo Mathews and Kusal Mendis really started to take the game by the scruff of its neck. The duo added 77-run stand with Mendis even getting to his 50 but then soon departed. Ajaz Patel has been the only bowler in the wicket column and rightfully so as he has been the best of the lot. Though New Zealand kept it tight, the lack of wickets would be a concern but with a new man set to join after the break, things are still evenly poised. Join us after a while for the final session of the day.

Lunch is taken now on Day 4! Sri Lanka have their task cut out on a wearing surface to scale down a target of 268. They are on the back foot at the moment but can learn from the way the Kiwi lower order fought.

54, 46, 36, 25 - These are the partnership runs for the last four wickets. This brilliant effort has lifted New Zealand from the doldrums and has put them in a commanding position. The Kiwis were reeling at one stage after Embuldeniya and Dhananjaya ran havoc but then BJ Watling emerged on the scene to strung in critical partnerships with the lower order. Tim Southee and William Somerville stuck in with the bat and Trent Boult played a handy cameo as well. Sri Lanka were completely off colour and lacked the intent with the ball.

Right then, after grinding for over two hours, Sri Lanka have finally managed to pick the remaining three wickets. New Zealand continued with their fight today morning and added another 90 runs to their lead.

OUT! Just by a fraction de Silva has got the wicket. The gamble to take the review almost paid off. Flighted delivery around off, skidding back in after landing, Ajaz looks to defend but misses. The ball hits him flush on the front pad. The Sri Lankan players put in a loud appeal and the umpire raises his finger. Ajaz takes the review with a glimmer of hope that something goes in his favour. Replay rolls in and shows that Dhananjaya de Silva's front foot was just, just around the crease. The line belongs to the umpire and the T.V umpire is happy with his front foot's landing. He then moves onto the Ball Tracker and it shows three reds. That will be the last action before Lunch. SRI LANKA NEED 268 TO WIN!
Ajaz Patel has been adjudged LBW. He has taken the DRS. It looks plumb but New Zealand have both the reviews left so they have just taken a chance here it seems.
Floated outside off, AP leaves it alone.
Tossed up on the pads, Somerville glances it towards fine leg for a single.
Floated on off, Ajaz strokes it to long off and gets to the other end.
FOUR! First boundary for Ajaz. It was a full delivery on the middle stump line. Ajaz goes for the slog sweep and hits it towards the deep mid-wicket fence for a boundary.
Flatter delivery on the pads, Somerville gets hit on the pads and goes towards fine leg and takes a  single.
Good length delivery on middle, Somerville plays it towards the mid-wicket region and takes a single. The lead is now 260.
Back of a length delivery on the off stump line, Somerville guides it to third man. No run.
On a good length outside off, Somerville drives it nicely towards mid off and takes a brace. Mathews runs after it and cleans it up.
Full delivery on the middle stump line, Somerville flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Good length delivery on the off stump, Patel guides it to third man and takes a single.
On a good length on off, Ajaz defends it towards the leg side.
Suranga Lakmal to try and end the New Zealand innings now.
Shorter on off, Somerville waits and then taps it wide of third man for a couple.
Floated on off, Patel strokes it towards cover for one.
Flights one outside off, Patel has nothing to do with it.
Floated on off, Patel defends it off the front foot.

NOT OUT! It's missing the stumps. Floated outside off, Ajaz covers his stumps and then decides to offer no shot. The ball though skids in to hit him on the pads. The Sri Lankan players appeal but the umpire says no. After a few words with his players, Dimuth signals the 'T'. Replays roll in and the Ball Tracker shows that the impact is way outside off. But since Patel was not offering any shot it won't matter much. Importantly for the Kiwis, it's missing the stumps quite easily.
Sri Lanka have taken the review for LBW. Ajaz Patel is the man in question. They have a review left and they have taken a chance.
Shorter on off, Ajaz gets on his back foot and defends it off the back foot.
Dhananjaya de Silva is back.
Short delivery on the off stump, which spun away from the batsman, Somerville looks to cut but due to the turn on it fails to put any bat on it.
Looped up ball on middle, Somerville blocks it back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery on middle, Ajaz flicks it off the front foot towards the mid-wicket region and takes a single.
Flatter delivery on middle, Somerville flicks it to mid-wicket and takes a single.
Shorter in length on off, William cuts it towards the point fielder.
Loopy delivery on off, William defends it to point.
The lead now goes past 250. Slowly but steadily New Zealand are taking this away from Sri Lanka. Floated around off, Ajaz sweeps it towards square leg for a couple.
Tossed up outside off, Patel leaves it alone.
Floated on middle and off, Ajaz defends it really well.
Flatter delivery on middle, WS flicks it to square leg and takes a single.
Flighted delivery on off, Somerville flicks it towards the leg side. No run.
Nicely looped up by Dananjaya on the off stump line, Ajaz pushes it to mid off and takes a single.
Floated outside off, Somerville looks to sweep but misses.
Play and a miss. Flighted outside off, Ajaz looks to drive but misses.
Flighted on off and middle, Ajaz gets down on one knee and sweeps it to square leg for a single.
Tossed up on middle, Somerville milks it to long on and gets to the other end.
Floated on middle and leg, Somerville gets on his back foot and pushes it to mid on.
Shorter on the pads, William looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Lasith Embuldenya is back.

Shout for an LBW! It is a flighted delivery on middle turning away from the batsman, Patel goes for a defensive shot but misses and gets hit on the pads. Akila appeals but is turned down. The Sri Lankan players do not go for the review. We are done with 100 overs now, New Zealand have put themselves in a commanding position.
Flighted delivery which spun away from the batsman, Patel while trying to defend misses the ball due to the spin on it.
Floated on middle, WS nudges it to long on for one.
Tossed up outside off, the ball spins in but does too much as Somerville looks to defend and misses to get hit on the front pad.
Flighted on off, Somerville defends it off the front foot.
Floated on off, Ajaz strokes it towards point for one.
BOUNCER! It was a very high one from Kumara and it went way above Somerville's head. William ducks under it.
Shorter delivery aimed at the body of Patel, the batsman rocks back and guides to cover and takes a single. Ajaz is off the mark with that single.
On a good length on middle, Ajaz pushes it to mid on.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Ajaz guides it to first slip.
Ajaz Patel walks out at number 11. Any runs from here are ultra bonus.

OUT! Caught! Boult's cameo comes to an end! He has played an entertaining and very important knock here. Lahiru bowls it short on middle and off, Boult hangs back and plays the upper cut. He connects well but he cannot get it wide enough of third man. Dhananjaya de Silva there runs to his right and takes a simple catch. The 36-run stand has been broken. Sri Lanka will be happy to see his back as he was creating a lot of nuisance out in the middle for them. Lead is 242!
Low full toss aimed at the middle stump, Boult who made room for himself by moving towards the leg side, drives it through the cover region and takes a brace.
Flighted delivery on the off stump line, Somerville defends it towards the leg side.
Looped up ball on off, Somerville defends it off the front foot.
Shorter delivery spinning into the batsman, Boult flicks it off his pads towards the square leg region and takes a single.

DROPPED AND SIX! Embuldeniya almost pulled out a stunner here. Tossed up on off and middle, Boult plays another brilliant shot after coming down the track. He gets to the pitch of the ball and smacks it over mid-wicket. Lasith Embuldeniya in the deep jumps and almost pulls it out of thin air but fails to hold on. The ball hits his hands and falls onto the ropes. Takes the partnership to 33 now.
Shorter delivery spinning into the batsman, Somerville rocks back and guides it to third man and takes a single. The lead now moves to 233 with that single.
Floated outside off, Somerville comes down the track and pads it away.
Akila Dananjaya is back on!

Another extraordinary shot from Boult. It was a full delivery on the leg stump line, Boult makes room towards the leg side and plays a lofted drive over the bowler's head for a brace. Mathews from mid on runs back and cleans it up before it reaches the ropes.

On a good length outside the off stump, Boult moves towards the off side and flicks it towards square leg. Boult is entertaining the fans over here. Rameez Raja on air has just called him in the Charlie Chaplin of batting! Hahaha!
Back of a length delivery on middle, William flicks it towards mid-wicket and takes off for a single.
Back of a length delivery on the pads, WS looks to flick but gets hit on the thigh pad and the ball rolls on to fine leg.
Pacy ball down the leg side, Somerville looks to glance but misses.
Short ball on the middle stump, Boult makes room for himself and pulls it straight towards long on and takes a single.
Floated around off, it is slightly short and spinning in. William waits for it and taps it towards first slip under his eyes.
Bowls it quicker just wide of the leg stump, Somerville looks to flick but misses.
FOUR! Brilliant shot from Somerville. It is a flighted delivery on middle, William goes for a slog sweep and hits it towards the mid-wicket region for a boundary. The lead moves to 228.
Fuller delivery which is converted to a full toss by Boult and played towards mid on for a single.
Full delivery on the middle stump, Boult goes for the reverse sweep but hits it straight to third man.
Tossed up on middle, Boult comes down the track and negates the spin. He glances it wide of long on and gets a brace.
OHH! This time Lahiru bowls this fuller aimed at the middle stump, Boult made room for himself towards the off side but still manages to flick it towards square leg for a single.
Shorter delivery outside the off stump line, Boult goes for the cut but is unable to put any bat on it.
Good length delivery on the middle stump line, Somerville pushes it towards the cover region and gives Boult the strike.
Another one on a length on off, Somerville pushes it towards mid off.
On a good length, on the off pole line, WS defends it towards the off side.
Shorter delivery aimed at the body, Somerville blocks it out.
Another play and miss. Floated around off, Boult looks to drive on the up again but once again misses.

SAFE! Boult never left and hence the lack of confidence from the Sri Lankan players. Flighted delivery on off, there is spin and bounce on this one. Boult looks to play a cover drive to follow up the boundary but misses. Dickwella takes the bails off in a flash and puts in an appeal. Boult looks in but the square leg umpire takes no chance and takes it upstairs. One replay is enough for the T.V umpire to show NOT OUT on the giant screen.
Stumping appeal taken upstairs. The Sri Lankan players are not too confident indicating Boult is in. Let's see what the replays have to say.

FOUR! Excellent use of the feet from Boult. It was a flighted delivery on off. Boult dances down the track and plays a lofted drive over the cover fielder for his second boundary. The ball goes between the long off and cover fielders.
Loopy delivery on the off stump line, Boult defends it off the front foot.
Slightly short and spinning away, Boult leaves it alone showing he is fully aware of his off stump.
Starts his new spell with a floated delivery on off, Boult gets behind the ball and blocks it.
Lasith Embuldeniya is back.
On a good length on off, Somerville defends it from the crease.
Back of a length delivery, WS punches it towards the off side.
Fuller delivery on off, Somerville drives this nicely but doesn't get it past the cover fielder.
BOUNCER! This one is way outside off and Somerville ducks under it.
Back of a length delivery on the off pole, Somerville punches this off the back foot towards the cover region and take a brace. The fielder at cover runs behind it and cleans it up.
On a good length ball on off stump, William pushes it to mid off.

Drinks Break! The day has so far belonged to New Zealand. They have got a lead of over 200 and are in the driver's seat. It has took Sri Lanka more than an hour to get their first wicket of the day but it was the big wicket of BJ Watling who has single-handedly dragged this game by the scruff of its neck.
Off spinner on off, Boult tucks it with the spin wide of mid-wicket for a couple.
Tossed up around off, Boult gets his front foot ahead and flicks it wide of short leg towards mid on.

Flighted delivery outside off, Boult comes across and looks to defend but misses. The ball hits him on his pad and there is an appeal for LBW but the umpire says no. Boult seemed to be a bit nervous as for some reason in a funny manner he points to the ball and lunges forward making it look like he was going to pick it up for a moment.

FOUR! First boundary for Boult. It is a full toss and Boult lunges forward and hits it straight down the ground for a boundary. Valuable runs these for the Kiwis. The lead moves to 211 with that shot.
Looped up delivery on off, Somerville drives this towards the cover fielder and takes a single.
BEATEN! Flighted delivery outside the off stump, William goes for the drive but gets beaten in air.
Full delivery on middle, Boult does well to block it out. Excellent first over by Trent!
BOUNCER! Good bowling from Lahiru. Bowled at the body. Boult uncomfortably tries to fend at it but misses it.
On a good length on the off pole, Trent defends it off the back foot towards mid off.
The new man in is Trent Boult.

OUT! Caught! Lahiru strikes! He has been waiting for his chance to bowl and has delivered as soon as he got hold of the ball. Lahiru hits the deck hard around off, it is in the corridor of uncertainty. Watling looks to defend but the extra pace and a hint of away movement get the better of him as he ends up getting a thick outside edge to the keeper. Dickwella takes an easy catch. Dimuth might have missed a trick here not getting Kumara earlier on but as the saying goes - Better late than never! End of a brilliant knock from BJ. He has played a critical role with the lower order batsmen and his efforts have taken his side to the lead of 206. End of the 46-run stand but a knock to remember from Watling, deserved a hundred but will have to be satisfied now with 77.
On a good length on the off stump, WS plays it towards the cover-point region and takes a single.
Back of a length delivery on off, William pushes it to cover.
Lahiru Kumara is on for the first time today.
Floated on off, Watling lunges forward and blocks.
Shorter on top of middle, Watling goes back and punches it to short mid-wicket.
Looped up ball on off, Watling blocks it out.
Flighted delivery on middle, Watling flicks it to short leg.
Looped up ball on off, William dances down the track and pushes it to mid off and goes for a quick single. The fielder has a direct hit at the bowler's end but the batsman is well in.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville lunges forward and defends it towards the leg side.
Fuller in length on the off pole, Watling blocks it towards the off side. Good over from Lakmal.
On a good length on middle, Watling plays it back to the bowler.
Loses his line here does Lakmal. It is bowled way down the leg side. Watling looks to flick but misses.
On a length and outside off, Watling lets it go to the keeper.
On a good length on the off pole, William pushes it to point and takes a single.
Back of a length delivery outside the off stump, Somerville goes for the cut off the back foot but outside edges it. Luckily for him, it falls just short of the gully fielder.
Watling uses his feet this time to come out of the crease. He, then, drives it through covers for a couple of runs.
Pulls his length back and bowls it short on middle, Watling gets on the back foot and taps it down to mid-wicket again.
Quicker and fuller on middle, helped on the leg side towards mid-wicket.
Shorter delivery which was bowled slower through the air. Somerville  pushes it easily towards the cover region and takes a single.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville defends it back to the bowler.
Shorter delivery on middle, turning into the batsman, Watling flicks it to the leg side for a single. The lead is now 200.
Angles in a length ball close to off, Somerville defends it from the back foot.

Stifled appeal for an lbw! Again not entertained by the umpire. Easily going down. An inswinger by Lakmal, landing on a length around middle, Somerville fails to flick and is pinged on the pads. Lakmal appeals but soon realized his fate.
Fractionally short and close to off, Watling plays late and eases it past the diving gully fielder for a run. 199 is the lead!
On a good length delivery on middle, Watling pushes it off the back foot towards the leg side.

Shout for an lbw! Not given. It is on a good length which jags back in and it hits Watling on the pads. There is a loud appeal for LBW but it's turned down. The Sri Lankans think of a review but opt against it. The replays show that the ball was just clipping the leg stump. It would have been umpire's call had they taken the review.
Good length delivery in the zone outside off, Watling pushes it out with an angled bat towards gully.
Beaten! Off spinner landing outside off, William tries to defend but it spins past his bat. Maiden from Dananjaya, lead remains two short of 200!
Floated delivery, full and close to off, William defends it close to his front pad.
Loopy and outside off, turning  back in, Somerville strides forward to defend it back but it spins back in to beat the inside edge.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
Tossed up ball on off, turning in sharply, William gets his bat down in time to keep it towards square leg.
Fullish and on off, it's defended back off the front foot.
Akila Dananjaya is back into the attack. Three close-in fielders around and there is a long on in place.

Lakmal bowls a good length delivery on the off pole, Somerville brings his bat down just in time and gets it away off a thick outside edge. It moves towards the point region and they take a single. The lead moves on to 198.
Another good length delivery on the middle pole, William blocks it towards mid off.
On a good length on off, Watling defends it to the off side and takes a single.
Good length delivery on middle, Watling plays it back to the bowler.
Another delivery on a length outside off, going straight on after landing, Watling covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Good length delivery in the channel outside off, Watling has a good look at it before making a leave.
Slower through the air, full and around off, Somerville is on the front foot as he gently pushes it to covers. Very solid. The lead is closing in on 200!

FOUR! Edgy but effective! It is an arm ball from Embuldeniya which is close to the off stump. William still goes for the cut and it goes off the outside edge between the first slip and the second slip fielders towards the third man fence.
Shorter in length on off, WS pushes it off the back foot towards point.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville blocks it out.
Looped up ball on middle, Somerville flicks it to short leg.
Flighted delivery on off, William pushes it to cover.
On a good length on the off pole, William defends it towards the point region and takes the single.
Good length delivery outside the off stump, Somerville shoulders arms to this one.
Lakmal keeps bowling it outside the off pole, Somerville has no problems in leaving it alone.
Another outswinger outside off stump, William leaves it alone.
Good length delivery outside the off stump, swinging away from the batsman, Somerville leaves it alone.
Play and a miss! Back of a length delivery outside off, Somerville spots the chance to exercise his arms and throws his bat at it. Fails to make any connection though.
Flighted delivery around the off stump, William lunges forward and drives it wide of cover and towards mid off for another run. Sensible.
Loopy delivery on off, Watling pushes it to covers and takes a single.
Flatter delivery on middle, William flicks it towards mid-wicket and takes a single as the bowler himself runs to the ball.
Shorter delivery on the off stump, Somerville attempts to cut but is unable to put bat on it.
BEATEN! Flighted delivery from Embuldeniya on the off stump, William looks to defend but misses due to the away spin. That was a peach and would have put even the best batsman in a spot.
Flighted delivery around off, good drift and it spins away a bit, Somerville covers the line and makes a brave leave.
On a good length shaping away from the batsman, Watling lets it go to the keeper.

Back of a length delivery outside the off stump, Watling plays a cracking cut shot towards the cover-point region and takes a brace. The fielder (Thirimanne) runs in from third man and makes an excellent diving stop.
Good length ball on the pads, William flicks it behind square leg and takes a single.
On a good length outside the off stump, Somerville leaves it alone.
BJ Watling walks up to his partner and has a quiet word. Just reminding him that there is no need to do anything fancy.
Good length delivery outside off stump, Somerville pokes at it but misses.
Full delivery on middle, William defends it towards mid on.
SECOND NEW BALL IS TAKEN! Crucial period of play coming up. Suranga Lakmal to continue from this end. Let's see if there is some extra zip and bounce from the surface. Two slips in place.
Looped up ball on middle, BJ defends it back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville sweeps it behind square leg for a run.
Loopy delivery on middle, Somerville defends it off the front foot.
Shorter in length this time, Watling rocks back and slaps it to cover for a single.
FOUR! Good shot from Watling. It was a full delivery from Embuldeniya and BJ sweeps it fine towards the fine leg region for a boundary. 200 up with that shot.
Loopy delivery on the pads, BJ defends it to the off side.

BOUNCER! A good one at that. It is aimed at the body and Somerville does well to duck under it. With a leg gully in place, the idea was to hurry up the batsman but William did well to hold his composure.
BEATEN! Good length delivery outside the off stump, Somerville goes for a drive but misses it completely.
This time, Suranga bowls a short delivery outside the off stump, Somerville lets it go.
Fuller in length on middle, William flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Good length delivery on middle, Somerville defends it towards the off side.
Starts with a nice and full delivery on off, Somerville solidly defends it back to the bowler.
So, just one over of spin from this end and Dimuth Karunaratne goes to Suranga Lakmal. A slip and gully in place.
Flatter one, full and on middle, Watling defends it off the front foot to the on side. Maiden!
Watling has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Embuldeniya gives this one a good toss. Lands it full and on off, Watling leans forward in defense.
Fires one in on middle, Watling covers the line, there isn't much spin and hence he defends it easily to the leg side.
Arm ball this time, around off and skidding back in, BJ is on the back foot in defense.
Floated delivery, full and on middle, Watling lunges and defends it to the off side.
Lasith Embuldeniya to bowl from the other end. He was impressive on Day 3, bagging 4 wickets so far. A slip and short leg in place.
Nicely defended. Slow spin back into the batsman from outside off, William sticks back and blocks it with soft hands.
Turning back in from around off, Somerville defends it comfortably in front of short leg.
Tossed up ball on middle, Watling flicks it past the left side of the leg slip fielder for a single.
Uses the spin this time. Somerville works it past short leg and gets off strike. First run of the day for the Kiwis!
Flatter through the air, around off, Somerville goes back inside the crease and defends.
Turn straightaway! Flighted and full on off, William is on the front foot to play that out but it turns in to take the inside edge. It rolls wide of short leg.

Right then, the waiting period is over and the players are making their way out to the middle. Akila Dananjaya to kickoff proceedings. A slip, leg slip and short leg in place. Here we go, Somerville is on strike.

Pitch report - Kyle Mills is down there to inspect the fourth day surface. He tells that from the Fort End, the spinners have bowled the most and there are a lot of footmarks present there. Not going to be easy to bat on this pitch.
Update 0950 local - Good news! In 45 minutes from now, Day 4 will be getting underway, weather permitting.

Update 0933 local - The drizzle isn't there any more and the groundsmen are doing their best to get the field ready for play. They are drying all the water on the covers at the moment. The pitch can be seen now. Best part of playing cricket in Sri Lanka is that they have huge covers so there should not be much delay. Stay tuned for more...

We can't fight nature but we can switch our focus on this match which is on a knife-edge at the moment. In spite of Sri Lanka dominating the majority of Day 3, New Zealand somehow fought back through BJ Watling's unbeaten knock and his crucial partnerships to gain the upper hand. The lead is currently 23 runs short of the 200-run mark and believe me, on this surface, it's going to be really tough to chase. As and when the weather permits, the first target of the home team will be to bundle out New Zealand as soon as possible and on the contrary, the Kiwis would love to swell their lead more. Exciting day ahead if the rain gods show some mercy.

Hello lovely people! Unfortunately, we are starting the day on a wet note. It's drizzling in Galle and it looks unlikely that we will be having a prompt start. The inclement weather has become a norm and we are seeing so many interrupted/abandoned games. But that's nature and just like you can't fight change, you can't fight gravity, you certainly can't fight nature. Let's make peace with that and hope the conditions improve soon so that we go ahead with this riveting Test match.
... DAY 4, FIRST SESSION ...

New Zealand lead by 177 runs at the moment and they would be eager to add as many more runs as possible. They would hope Watling could bat till the end and the others just stay there with him. Sri Lanka on the other hand, need to get the last three wickets quickly as the lead the Kiwis have now, is already going to be a tricky total to chase. Also, if Sri Lanka chase the target given to them, it is going to be the highest chase on this ground. They will have to bat really well to do so but for now, the remaining three wickets is their issue. Day 4 will probably give us a very nice idea to which way this game is going. Do join us at 0945 local (0415 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

First it was Latham and Nicholls who steadied the ship with a 50-run stand but then both were dismissed in quick succession. Sri Lanka were still on top at that time but then, the stand which probably could prove to be the game-changing one, the partnership between Southee and Watling which accounted for 54 took the Kiwis to safer shores. The former was dismissed but then Somerville hung in there with Watling who has surpassed his half ton.

End of another excellent day of cricket. Still, it is difficult to decide on which way this game is heading too. However, it is New Zealand who will be the happier side at the moment but it was Sri Lanka who dominated majority of the day. The Lankans started by adding handy runs with the bat early on and taking a lead of 18. They then got rid of the top order quickly. Embuldeniya was the tormentor-in-chief. It seemed like they would run through the Kiwi batting line-up but that was not to be.
IT IS STUMPS ON DAY 3! This was expected, once they went off, chances of them coming back and resuming play was very bleak.

Well, the umpires have offered light to the batters, they have taken it and off go the players. That should probably be it for the day too. No official word yet. It has gotten quite dark out there and difficult to see it brightening up now. A round of applause for Watling as he makes his way back into the dressing room and it is well deserved. He has been the hero for New Zealand.
On the pads again, this is worked through square leg for one.
From over the wicket, he lands it outside leg, Somerville lunges and keeps it out.
Floats it up outside off, Watling strokes it through covers for one.
Floats it up on the middle stump, Watling comes down the track and works it to mid-wicket.
Loopy ball on off, Watling lunges and keeps it out.
On off, Watling defends it.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
A bumper, WS ducks under it.
Short ball on the pads, Somerville looks to flick but gets an inside edge to the thigh pad and the ball rolls on towards fine leg.
Another short one on the body, Somerville ducks under it.
A short one but it is down the leg side. Somerville evades it.
Lovely fielding! This is fuller and around off, Watling creams it towards cover where the fielder dives to his left and stops it. Saves at least two.
Looped up delivery on the middle stump, William blocks it out.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville defends it back to the bowler.
Short delivery on off stump, Watling cuts towards cover and takes a single.
Loopy delivery on middle, Watling defends it off the front foot.
Another flighted delivery on middle, Watling comes down the track and pushes it to mid on.
Flighted delivery on middle, Watling blocks it out.
Good length ball on the off stump, Somerville defends it off the front foot. Good over from Lahiru.
BOUNCER! A good one at that. It was aimed at the body. Somerville does well to duck under it.
Good length delivery outside off, Somerville leaves it alone.
Another back of a length delivery, William blocks it out of the back foot.
Back of a length delivery on off, Somerville defends it off the back foot.
Good length ball around off, Somerville stands tall and punches it through cover for a couple.
Loopy delivery on off, Watling plays it to covers.
Tossed up on off, Watling defends it off the back foot.
Flighted delivery on off, Watling blocks it off the back foot.
Floated delivery on middle, Somerville flicks it towards mid-wicket for a run.
Tossed up on off, Somerville blocks it off the back foot.
Flighted delivery on middle, Somerville defends it off the front foot.

FOUR! Back to back boundaries for Watling. This one is bowled short and outside off stump. Watling just rocks back and guides it over gully for a boundary. Excellent batting this from BJ. He moves on to 60 with that shot.
FOUR! Brilliant shot from Watling. It is a full delivery on middle, Watling drives it straight past the mid on fielder for a boundary. Watling is playing an amazing knock here.
Good length delivery on off, Somerville pushes it to cover for a single.
BOUNCER! Not a good one at that. It was bowled way outside off and Somerville does not feel the need to play at it. He lets it go back to the keeper.
Another back of a length delivery outside off stump, Watling cuts it towards cover for a single.

NOT OUT! A big LBW shout. It is a back of a length delivery on middle, Watling tries to flick but gets hit flush on the pads. There is a strong appeal for LBW but is turned down. The Sri Lankan players think of a review but opt against it.
A dot to end a successful over for Embuldeniya. On off, Somerville keeps it out.
William Somerville is the new batsman in.

OUT! STUMPED! The dropped catch does not cost Sri Lanka a lot. Finally they manage to get the breakthrough. A very, very good partnership for the Kiwis though. Southee walks back after playing a handy innings. New Zealand are effectively 160 for 7 now. Embuldeniya gets his fourth. He tosses it up above the eye line. Seeing that, Southee comes down the track. He though is beaten by the dip and the turn away as he looks to drive. The keeper collects and whips the bails off. Sri Lanka would now really hope to take the last three wickets quickly.
Tossed up on middle, Southee defends it out.
Floated delivery on off, Southee defends it off the front foot.

Another session that belonged to the hosts. They have scalped 5 wickets and are now into the bowlers with New Zealand's lead just 106. It has been the spinners who have spun the web and done the damage with Embuldeniya, the star with three wickets. Apart from a 56-run stand between Latham and Nicholls, nothing else has been substantial from the visitors. With BJ Watling, the only recognized batsman out in the middle will hold the key. Sri Lanka will look to restrict them under 150 and New Zealand, on the other hand, will be looking to get closer to 200. What will happen? Join us in a while for the final session of Day 3.

Tossed up on the pads, Henry glances it to the on side and keeps the strike.
Shorter on off, TL strokes it to point for a single.
On the pads, Latham turns it to leg gully.

SIX! If you hit it then hit it clean and that is exactly what Latham has done here. Tossed up delivery on middle and leg, Tom comes down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and heaves it over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie. No one in the deep so once he got any sort of decent connection he was going to be safe.
FOUR BYES! Floated on the pads, it spins away from the batsman. Latham looks to flick but misses. Dickwella too misses to collect and the ball goes behind to the fine leg fence.

NOT OUT! Latham is safely home! Tossed up on middle and leg, Latham comes down the track and tucks it towards mid on and calls for a quick single. Mathews gets to the ball and scores a direct hit at the bowler's end. The ball deflects behind and they take a second run. The umpire goes to the T.V umpire and replay shows Latham is safely in.
Run Out appeal taken upstairs. Latham is the man in question, the Sri Lankan players do not look too confident.
Bowls a flighted delivery on the off stump, Nicholls attempts to defend it but gets an outside edge towards the slip region.
Flighted delivery on the off stump, Nicholls blocks it out.
Flighted delivery on the middle stump, Nicholls defends it to the off side.
Flighted delivery on the middle pole, Nicholls defends it off the front foot back to the bowler.
Tossed up on middle, Henry keeps it out.
Slower and shorter on middle and leg, Nicholls defends it.
Shorter in length this time, Latham tries to flick it on the leg but it falls just short of the short fine leg fielder. Excellent over from Embuldeniya.
Another flighted delivery, Nicholls flicks to square leg and gets off the mark with a single..
Flighted on leg, Nicholls guides it to short fine leg.
The new man in is Henry Nicholls. He was good in the 1st innings but needs to better that effort here.

OUT! Caught! It is getting bad to worse here for New Zealand. Don't know what Taylor was thinking here. His side are already two down and yet he goes for a counter-attacking approach which is not needed at all at this stage. Embuldeniya bowls a flighted ball outside off, Taylor comes down the track and goes for a big smash on the off side. The ball spins away and takes the outside edge of the bat. It goes straight to Dhananjaya de Silva at first slip, who is one of the best Sri Lankan fielders. He won't drop those and he does not. Second wicket for Lasith Embuldeniya and it's two massive fishes here.
Flatter delivery on the leg stump, Latham rocks back and flicks it to square leg for a single.
Loopy delivery on the middle stump, Taylor comes down the track and plays it to mid on for a single.
Flighted on off and middle, Latham bends his back and defends it to get through the over.
Arm ball outside off, Latham reads it well and leaves it alone.
Akila goes short around off, Latham gets on his back foot and punches it to cover.
Tossed up on off, Latham calmly defends it off his front foot.
Dananjaya gives this one a lot of air and bowls it on middle, Taylor milks it to long on and eases to the other end.
Akila floats one down the leg side, Taylor looks to flick but luckily he does not get any feather on it.
The batsman has played it towards mid-wicket. They pick up a single.
Latham works it with the angle towards mid-wicket for one.
Ross Taylor is the new man in. The top scorer of the first innings for New Zealand. Something similar is needed from him.

OUT! In the air... Kusal Perera seems to have misjudged it but he hangs on in the end. Falls on his back. A huge, huge wicket for Sri Lanka. They have got New Zealand's best batter with the lead at 2. Body blow this for New Zealand as they needed a big effort from their skipper but it is not to be. Williamson was getting bogged down and he looks to break free here. He steps down the track to this flighted delivery on middle. He does not get to the pitch of the ball but still goes ahead with the shot. He only manages to hit it high in the air behind mid on. Perera runs back, he does not seem very comfortable under it but still manages to take it behind him. The Lankans are ecstatic and Williamson walks back disappointed. Back-to-back failures for him. You do not see that often. Sri Lanka right on top here.
Floated delivery on off, the skipper drives it to mid off.
Tossed up on middle, Williamson comes down the track and keeps it out.
Full toss on off, Williamson drives it to covers.
Lasith Embuldeniya to partner Akila Dananjaya.
Tossed up on middle, Latham defends it out.
Outside off, Latham leaves it alone.
Flighted delivery on middle, Williamson comes down the track and flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen cross ends.
Floated delivery on middle, Latham flicks it towards mid-wicket for a single. New Zealand get into the lead now.
BEATEN! Tossed up outside off, Latham looks to defend but misses it due to the spin on this one.
Flighted delivery on off, Latham defends it off the front foot.
We are back for the afternoon session on Day 3. Tom Latham walks out with his skipper, Kane Williamson to resume their innings. Sri Lanka continue with spin as Akila Dananjaya starts the new session.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

For Sri Lanka, it was once again the spinners who did the majority of the bowling. They did get some purchase but the wicket still seems a decent one to bat on. One would believe it is going to be hard work for the bowlers if the Kiwi batters play with determination. An important passage of play awaits after the break. Do join us in a while.

Sri Lanka's session easily! First they took the lead, yes a slender one but still it could prove vital and then they have managed to pick a wicket too. New Zealand at present are effectively 0 for 1. They now though have Kane Williamson and Tom Latham out there and they would hope the two can bat for long. A lot will be expected from the New Zealand skipper in this innings and he needs to step up if New Zealand are to get into a strong position.

Just, just! That missed the off pole by a whisker. This is floated up on off, Williamson defends outside the line. It hits the inside edge and rolls agonizingly close past the off pole. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3!
Loopy delivery on the off stump, Kane flicks it to mid on.
Flighted delivery on the off stump, Kane guides it to third man. No Run.
Loopy delivery on the off stump, Kane defends it off the front foot back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery on the middle stump, Kane defends but the ball almost rolls on back to the stumps. It hits the pad of Williamson and it rolls to first slip.

This is angled into the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On stumps, this is defended.
Another loopy ball on off, blocked.
Flighted ball on middle, this is defended.
On off, Latham pushes it to covers.

Akila Dananjaya is back into the attack.
Flighted delivery on the off stump, Williamson has blocked it back to the bowler.
Looped up ball on middle stump, Kane defends it off his front foot back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery on the off pole, Williamson prods forward and pushes it towards cover.
Shorter delivery outside the off stump, Latham cuts it to cover and takes a single.
Loopy delivery on the off stump, Latham comes down the track and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Flatter and on off, Latham goes back and keeps it out.
Lasith Embuldeniya is on now!
Short delivery on the middle stump, Williamson flicks it to the leg side. No run.
Flighted delivery on the middle pole, Kane plays it towards short leg.
Shorter in length this time on the middle stump, Williamson plays it back to the bowler.
Loopy delivery on the middle stump, Kane defends it back to the bowler.
Shorter in length outside the off stump, Latham cuts it past cover for a single.
Floats it up outside off, it has been left alone.
Good length ball on the middle pole, Latham flicks it to fine leg and crosses over for a single.
On a good length on the off stump, Kane guides it towards third man and takes a single.

Fuller in length this time on the middle pole, Kane plays it back to the bowler.
NO BALL! Lakmal oversteps once again. It was a back of a length delivery on the middle stump, Williamson defends it back to the bowler.
Good length delivery on the off stump, Kane plays it late towards the gully fielder.
This is on the pads, Latham works it down to fine leg for one.
Flighted delivery on the off stump, Williamson pushes it towards cover.

OVERTHROWS! Loopy delivery on the off stump, Williamson defends it to the off side and takes a single. The fielder throws it at the stumps but misses. It is a wayward throw and the ball goes past the keeper allowing the batsman to take another run. Unnecessary from Sri Lanka this.
Kane Williamson is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! New Zealand lose their first wicket even before they cut their deficit. Dhananjaya de Silva is the man who draws first blood for Sri Lanka. A soft dismissal this. De Silva bowls this on off, the ball comes slow off the surface. Raval looks to push at it but is already into the shot. The ball ends up chipping it to the fielder at cover where Karunaratne makes no mistake. Early wicket for Sri Lanka, just what they would have wanted. They would be eager for another before the Lunch interval.
Another flighted delivery on the middle pole, Raval defends it back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery outside the off stump, Latham prods forward and pushes it towards mid on for a single.
Loopy delivery on the middle pole, Latham defends it back to the bowler.
Length delivery on middle, Latham flicks it towards square leg for a run.
On a good length on off, Latham drives it straight back towards the bowler.
Good length delivery on off, Latham blocks it off the back foot.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Latham looks to defend but misses it due to the away movement on this one. Dickwella appeals for a caught behind but the umpire shakes his head.
On a good length and outside off, Latham shoulders his arms to this one.
Lakmal bowls a short delivery, Raval pulls it through square leg for a run.
Tossed up outside off, Latham does not bother to play at that.
Flighted delivery on middle, Latham keeps it out.
Outside off, Latham leaves it alone.
Floated delivery on off, Latham punches it to point.
Tossed up outside off, Latham lets it go.
Flighted delivery on off, Latham defends it off the back foot.
Dhananjaya de Silva is into the attack.
BOUNCER! Lakmal pitches this one outside off stump and the ball rises to the keeper. Raval shoulders arms to it.

Not out!  Fuller in length this time on the pads, Raval gets hit on the pads while trying to flick it. The Sri Lankans put in a huge appeal for LBW but the umpire does not give it out. They think for a review but opt against it. In the end it was a good decision as the ball was going down the leg side.
Loses the line does Lakmal, It was a short ball on the pads and Raval lets it go back to the keeper.
BOUNCER! A good one from Lakmal. Raval does not play at it and ducks under it. The umpire does not give it a wide as he thinks it is fine.
Another good length delivery on the middle pole, Latham flicks it towards mid-wicket for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the stump but Raval is well in.
On a good length on the off pole, Latham defends it back to the bowler.
NO BALL! Lakmal oversteps here. It is a good length delivery outside the off stump. Latham lets it go back to the keeper.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A little fuller this time, Raval lunges and keeps it out.
On the stumps again but the length is shorter, Raval goes back and pushes it back to the bowler.

A couple! This is outside off and flatter, Raval plays it late and down towards third man for two.

Good length delivery on the off stump, Latham defends it off the back foot back to the bowler.
On a good length outside the off stump, Latham has no business with it and lets it go back to the keeper.
Back of a length delivery outside the off stump, Latham lets it go back to the keeper.
On a good length on the off stump, Latham gets an inside edge attempting to push it towards the off side, onto his boots and rolls towards the off side.
OHH! Good delivery from Lakmal. It was a good length delivery around the off stump. Latham leaves it alone but the ball just whizzed past the off stump. It is a good leave in the end from Latham.
Good length ball on the pads, Raval flicks it towards square leg and takes a single. Raval and New Zealand are off the mark.
On middle, Latham goes back and defends it onto the ground. Two maidens in a row!
Outside off and spinning away further. Latham lets it be.
Shorter and quicker again on off, Tom defends it.
Flatter and quicker and on off, Latham works it to mid-wicket.
Slows it up and lands it on off, it pitches and once again spins away. Latham looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards point.
Floats it up on off, it pitches and turns away. Latham lets it be.
Spin from the other end. Akila Dananjaya comes to bowl.
On a good length this time from Lakmal, Jeet defends it again. Good start from Suranga Lakmal as it is a maiden.
Another back of a length delivery on the off stump, Raval pushes it back towards the bowler.
Back of a length delivery, Jeet blocks it back to the bowler.
Good length delivery on the off stump, Raval defends it towards gully.
On a good length on the leg stump, Raval defends it towards mid-wicket.
Starts with a good length delivery on the pads, Raval gets hit on the pads while defending it. There is a stifled appeal for LBW but the umpire is unmoved.
That's all we have from this Test match. The second one starts on 22nd August at the P Sara Oval in Colombo at 1000 local (0430 GMT). Do join us then. Cheers!

Sri Lankan skipper and the MAN OF THE MATCH, Dimuth Karunaratne states that it's not easy chasing in the fourth innings. Emphasizes on the importance of forming a good partnership and this is something he discussed with Lahiru Thirimanne. Tells that once you are set in these conditions you have to make the most of it. Adds that they want to stick to the basics in the next Test match as well. Praises his bowlers for their performance in the first innings. Mentions that once the ball gets softer, it's easier to bat in Galle. Further says that they saw how Taylor and Watling batted on this pitch and their knocks made them believe that it's not too dangerous to bat on.

New Zealand skipper, Kane Williamson starts by saying that at the toss, he would have taken a target of 268 in the fourth innings. Adds that from their past experience they thought the surface will deteriorate but it didn't much. Feels the surface slowed down and it was a good one for batting. Mentions that they have learnt a lot from this game. States that they weren't too far behind Sri Lanka but the hosts had the experience of playing in their backyard which came in handy. Admits that they need to bat and bowl better and concentrate on getting partnerships. On the Test ranking, Kane replies that it's secondary and the quality of cricket is what they focus on. Signs off by saying that this wasn't their best performance and congratulates Sri Lanka for playing really well.

With this defeat, New Zealand's chance of winning the series 2-0 and toppling India from the number one Test position has also vanished. For Sri Lanka, they get 60 points for winning this match and have opened their account in the ICC World Test Championship. Stay with us for the presentation...

This Test match could have been over in a flash had BJ Watling not stepped up for the Black Caps in the second innings. He revived things for the visitors with his brave knock and handy partnerships with the lower order batsmen. With the pitch showing signs of deterioration, a target of 268 was considered to be a tricky one but when your openers raise a 161-run partnership, things become smooth more often than not. Kudos to Karunaratne for his stupendous innings and Sri Lanka were also helped by some ordinary performance by New Zealand in the field.

The result doesn't really show how closely this Test match was fought. The momentum kept swinging like a pendulum and it was Sri Lanka who got the early advantage after Akila Dananjaya's fifer. But Ross Taylor's knock made sure that the Kiwis somehow limped to a respectful first innings total. Then it was the turn of the Lankan batsmen to dominate proceedings although it didn't last for long as courtesy of Ajaz Patel's 5-wicket haul, the visitors only conceded a slender 18-run lead.

A convincing victory for Sri Lanka to go 1-0 up in the series! Skipper Dimuth Karunaratne was the chief architect of this win. His individual century coupled with the 161-run stand with Lahiru Thirimanne has powered the Islanders home. New Zealand were decent with their bowling efforts but were let down by some sloppy fielding. Karunaratne will be a delighted man after winning his first home Test as a captain and also he keeps his 100 percent win record intact.
That is it! Mathews takes Sri Lanka home. Good length ball on middle and off, Angelo shuffles and turns it behind square on the leg side to seal the game. SRI LANKA WIN BY 6 WICKETS!
Good length ball outside off, Dhananjaya calmly leaves it alone.
No hurry as de Silva is not interested in playing this length ball outside off.
FOUR! Just a run away from a historic chase here in Galle. Short ball on off, de Silva gets on his back foot and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Straight as an arrow. Full ball on middle, Mathews plays a good looking straight drive but it is too straight as the ball ricochets off the stumps and goes wide of mid on. Single taken.
On off, Mathews defends it off the front foot.
Good length ball around off, Mathews stands tall and punches it to cover.

Full on off, Dhananjaya drives it straight but the bat turns in his hands and he ends up mistiming it past the stumps at the non-striker's end. The batsmen come back for the second as the fielder from mid off cleans it up. Just 6 needed now.
On top of middle, Dhananjaya defends it with a straight bat.
Short from Southee, Mathews eases his pull towards fine leg for one.
Fuller on off, Angelo pushes it to mid off.
Back of a length ball on off, Mathews is in no hurry and calmly defends it off his back foot.
Bouncer! Mathews sees it and ducks under it.

Common sense has prevailed! Well done. The extra 15 minutes are over but they are staying to finish this match as only 9 more runs are needed. Hang on, extra 15 minutes or 4 overs, that's the rule and it's only 3 so far. Hmm...
On a good length ball outside the off stump, Dhananjaya leaves it alone.
Back of a length delivery around off, de Silva punches this one off the back foot.

FOUR! Lovely shot! Southee bowls this one on the pads, Dhananjaya flicks this towards the square leg fence. The fielder from fine leg comes running and tries to make a diving stop but his leg gets stuck on the ground. The ball goes through and into the fence. 9 more runs needed.
Full delivery on the off stump line, Dhananjaya pushes it to cover. No run.
Short ball outside the off stump, Mathews rocks back and cuts it towards point for a single.
Good length delivery by Southee first up, Mathews flicks it to square leg.
Tim Southee is back into the attack.
On a good length on middle, Dhananjaya defends it towards the leg side.
FOUR! Crashed! It is a length ball way outside off, de Silva goes for it and hammers it between the point and cover fielders for a boundary. Dhananjaya gets off the mark with that shot.
Good length delivery on middle, Dhananjaya defends it to square leg.
On a good length on middle, de Silva flicks it to mid-wicket.
Dhananjaya de Silva is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! An entertaining cameo comes to an end from Kusal Perera. It is a good length delivery on middle and leg, Perera dances down the track with the intention of going big over the leg side. But it doesn't come properly off his bat and he ends up handing a simple catch to Santner at mid on. Kusal was trying to finish things quickly and perished in that effort. 18 more required.
BEAUTIFUL! Another outswinger from Boult. It is a good length delivery outside the off stump, Perera pokes at it and luckily does not get an edge on it.
Comes from 'round the wicket and delivers it around off, Mathews walks down the track and then pads it away.
Gets forward and defends it towards short leg.
Quicker and on the pads, helped out on the leg side.
Sliding down the leg side, Mathews fails to work it away.
FOUR! Poor delivery and the watchful Mathews has decided to punish it. Short and on middle, Angelo rocks back and pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
Spinning down the leg side, Mathews tries to flick but misses. The keeper collects the ball but Angelo does well to plant his back leg inside the crease just in time.

With 22 runs needed more, the umpires have decided to extend the first session by 15 minutes. Usually, it's 30 minutes but since we started 15 minutes early and a morning session cannot be more than 150 minutes, they have done so.

FOUR! Hammered! It is a good length ball outside off, Perera charges down the track and hammers it over the cover fielder for a boundary. Perera moves to 23 with that boundary. The hosts need 22 more runs.
OHH! A terrific yorker with a hint of away shape, Perera is late to get his bat down and the ball goes through. It just misses the off stump by a whisker.
Good length delivery on middle, Mathews plays it to the cover region and takes a single.
On a good length ball on off, Mathews drives this towards mid off. No run.
Full delivery on the middle stump line, Mathews blocks it to square leg.

Good start from Boult. It is an inswinging delivery on the off stump line, Mathews looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The Kiwis appeal but the umpire is unmoved. The replays show that it came off the inside edge.
SECOND NEW BALL IS TAKEN! Trent Boult to make first use of it. 27 runs needed more.
Shortish and around off, Mathews turns it through square leg for one.
Flatter and shorter on middle, punched through covers for a run.

PERERA IS SAFE AGAIN! Tossed up ball landing full around off, Perera tries to play the reverse sweep but fails to make any connection. He is pinched on the back leg, they appeal but the umpire remains unmoved. New Zealand review the decision but the Hawk Eye shows that the impact was outside the line of off stump.
Shout for an lbw! Not given by the umpire. New Zealand have reviewed it. Possibly, the impact is outside off. Ultra Edge has found no bat. And the Hawk Eye confirms that the impact is outside off.
Uses his feet once more and this time he has eased it down through mid on for a run. 7 minutes to go for Lunch, 29 needed more. They have the option of extending the first session.
Shortish and on middle, skidding down, Angelo tries to work it around but fails to connect.
Jumps out of the crease to a full ball around off and then defends it back to the bowler.

FOUR! Beautiful shot from Perera. Southee bowls this fuller on middle, Kusal comes one step down and plays an excellent drive straight down the ground for a boundary. Perera has moved to 18 off just 13 balls. 30 more runs required for the hosts. With Perera in, it looks likely that the match will finish before Lunch.
BEAUTIFUL! Another good length delivery from Southee, Perera looks to poke at it but changes his mind at the last moment. He gets his bat out and lets it go to the keeper.
On a good length ball outside off, Perera leaves it alone.
FOUR! Kusal wants to finish this quickly. On a good length this one from Southee. Kusal hoicks this over the mid-wicket fielder for a boundary. KP is in the mood today.
Full delivery on the off stump line, Mathews punches this one down to mid off and takes a single.
On a good length outside off, Mathews lets it go to the keeper.
Uppish but safe! Spinning away from the batsman, Kusal tries to drill his drive through covers but it takes the outside half of his bat and rolls to the right of the point fielder.

SAFE! Kusal Perera tries to be fancy with his reverse-batted shot but fails to make proper connection. The ball has flown from something and the second slip fielder has caught it. The umpire has given it out as well. Perera waits before taking the referral. He consults Angelo and then takes the DRS. A bit odd. He must be knowing if that hit his gloves or bat. Anyway. Is there bat? Is there glove? Nothing on the Ultra Edge and it has struck him on the forearm, just above the wrist band. As per the norm, they check for the lbw as well but the impact is with the umpire's call.
Time to trouble the third umpire! Kusal Perera is given out caught at second slip. He has taken the DRS after consulting his partner. Let's find out what happened there in the replays...

FOUR! Excellent shot from Perera. It is a loopy delivery on off, Perera comes down the track and hits it past the diving mid on fielder for a boundary. Perera is looking dangerous here. 20 more minutes of him and the game will be over for the visitors.
OHH! Lucky! It is a flighted delivery around off, Perera goes for the cut but inside edges it almost onto the off stump. It goes in between the keeper's legs towards the third man region for a brace.

That's more like it, quips Russel Arnold on air. A delivery in the zone outside off, Kusal takes his front leg forward before making another leave. No need to do anything silly.

Time for some pace! Tim Southee is into the attack now. A slip and gully in place. There is a short mid-wicket as well in a catching position.

Change of ends for William Somerville. Two slips present for the left-hander.

Drinks break. New Zealand have managed to pick a couple of wickets in the morning session but Sri Lanka have also made steady progress in this run chase. They are now just 75 runs away from the target. The bowling from the Black Caps have been a lot better today but they need to do better with their close-in catching. Let's see how the second half of the first session pans out.
Loopy delivery on middle, Angelo blocks it back to the bowler.
Shorter delivery on middle, Mathews blocks it out off the back foot.
Looped up ball on middle, Mathews defends it towards the off side.

FOUR! 9th Test hundred for Dimuth Karunaratne, fifth while batting in the third or fourth innings of a Test match. That tells volumes about his calibre. The pitch is not an easy one to bat on but the Lankan skipper has applied himself and put his side in the driver's seat in this tricky run chase. He reaches there by dancing down the track and heaving a full ball with the spin. Lovely connection and it's a boundary at mid-wicket. Dimuth raises his bat in celebration. Wonderful knock so far and he would love to be there till the end.
Flighted delivery on off, Mathews defends it towards the point region and takes a single.

Nicely flighted delivery, full and on off, Mathews draws forward in defense.
Floated and full on off, Mathews is forward in defense.
Skips down the track to a full ball and drives it to long on for a single.
Extra turn and bounce from outside off, Dimuth fails to work it away and is hit high on the front leg.
Defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Fires in a flatter and very full ball on off, Angelo pushes it through mid off for a single.
Flighted delivery on middle, Karunaratne defends it off the front foot.
Looped up ball on off, Dimuth defends it back to the bowler.

OHH! Mathews gets off the mark with a streaky single. It is a flighted delivery on middle, Angelo looks to flick but due to the spin on it, he flicks it uppishly towards short leg. Latham is unable to react quickly and the ball goes through his hands towards square leg.

OUT! Mendis batted like a train on fire but the Kiwis have extinguished that fire pretty quickly. Ajaz serves a tossed up ball outside off, the length is very full around off, not quite there to slog but Mendis still attempts it by going down on one knee. Fails to get it from the middle of the bat and it flies straight into the hands of Jeet Raval at mid-wicket. Good sharp reaction catch by the Kiwi opener. Sri Lanka have lost a couple of quick wickets here and need to watch out for a collapse.
Flatter and shorter on off, Mendis tries to cut but mistimes it on the off side.
Helps it off his pads to square leg for one.
Quicker one outside off, skidding off the surface, Karunaratne plays it late and guides it fine past first slip for a couple of runs.
Walks down the track and flicks it to mid-wicket.

SIX! This one has travelled all the way! Kusal Mendis has come out with some positive intent. Shows fancy footwork once again. A flighted full ball around off, Mendis dances down the track, goes with the spin and powers it over long on. 10 runs and a wicket from the over, an eventful one! Under 100 needed now.
Fuller and on middle, gently pushed across the line on the leg side.
FOUR! That's the way to deal with extra spin or bounce. Just don't allow it to do its bit. Mendis is down the track in a flash and heaves it over wide mid on for a boundary.

Nervy beginning for Kusal! Somerville straightaway gets it to spin and bounce into the batsman from around middle. Mendis tries to flick but it takes the inside half of his blade and flies just past short leg.
Kusal Mendis walks in next with 107 runs needed more for a win.

OUT! Good review by New Zealand and they have managed to break this massive opening stand. It's a nicely tossed up delivery, landing full around middle and leg. Thirimanne sees the line and length closely and finds it good enough to opt for the sweep shot. He goes down on one knee to execute it but the ball straightens after landing, beats his bat and pings him on the pads. The appeal for an lbw follows but the umpire remains unmoved. Kane Williamson goes for the DRS and to his delight everything is fine in the replays. No bat involved, pitching in line, impact in line and it's hitting the leg pole. End of a fine knock by Lahiru, a career saving one? That only time will tell.

Huge shout for an lbw! Not given. DRS time! Kane Williamson will have to take it with nothing much happening. The big question here is that has the delivery straightened enough after landing? The Ultra edge has detected nothing but the Hawk Eye is showing that it's hitting leg. New Zealand have the breakthrough they dearly needed.
Darts it in, very full and around off, Thirimanne gets right behind the line and blocks it on the off side.
Shorter delivery outside the off stump, Thirimanne rocks back and slaps it through the cover region and run through for three. Thirimanne will keep the strike for the next over.
Looped up ball on middle, Thirimanne flicks it off his pads towards short leg.
Flighted delivery on middle, Dimuth comes down the track and plays it towards mid on for a single.
Shorter delivery on middle, Dimuth flicks it to short leg.

Big shout for LBW! Flighted delivery on middle spinning into the batsman, Dimuth looks to flick but gets hit on the front pad. The Kiwi players put in a huge appeal but it is turned down. They think of a review but opt against it and rightly so as the ball was drifting down the leg stump.
Loopy delivery on off, Dimuth defends it to the off side.

Works it with the spin on the leg side, finds mid-wicket.

Leans forward to a full ball and defends it on the leg side.
Another delivery fired in. It's short and close to off stump. Karunaratne stays back to cut but misses. Too close to the body, that.
Flatter one, a touch short and on off, Dimuth blocks it off his back foot to the off side.
Defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

Pushes this one quicker through the air. Lands it full and around off, gets it to spin away as well. Karunaratne is on the front foot as he pushes at it with an angled bat. Does well to do so with soft hands and edges it wide of second slip.
Loopy delivery on middle, Lahiru flicks it towards square leg and takes another single.
Short delivery on middle, Dimuth reverse sweeps it towards the point region and takes a single.
Flatter delivery on middle, Dimuth blocks it out.

FOUR! First boundary of the day for the hosts. It is a flighted delivery on the off pole, Dimuth flicks it with the spin towards the mid-wicket region for a boundary. Excellent shot this. 125 more needed for the hosts.

Flighted delivery on off, Dimuth looks to flick but gets hit on the front pad.

Starts with a flighted delivery wide outside off. It turns back in from there as Karunaratne pads it away. A stifled appeal but it dies down quickly.
As expected, spin from both ends. Ajaz Patel to bowl...

Looped up ball on middle, Lahiru defends it back to the bowler.
